U.S. Embassy Announces the Lower Mekong Initiative English for Special Purposes Program (ESP).

Participants must:
. Be mid to upper level professionals and officials;
. Have a lower intermediate level of English;
. Be in a position to influence policy or speak about policy in the given topic area of the seminar;
. Need English for attending regional and international meetings, conferences and seminars or drafting documents and proposals;
. Be able to commit to attend the entire eight day workshop (this may require additional time for travel to another country); and
. Be able to commit to about 3 hours a week for the follow-up distance education sessions over a 4 to 5 week period.

Click the link below for more information.
http://cambodia.usembassy.gov/122711_pr.html

Are you interested in spending 4 months in the U.S. working at community-based organizations and government agencies?

Fore more information, click the link below (PDF: 150 KB).
http://goo.gl/FuFi5

ELIGIBILITY REQUIREMENTS:

Candidates will be considered without respect to race, color, religion, national origin, or gender.

Persons with disabilities are strongly encouraged to apply.

Competition for the Community Solutions Program is merit-based and open to community leaders, ages 25-38 at the time of application, who meet the following criteria:

 Is from a participating country (U.S. citizens, permanent residents of the U.S. , and individuals who have applied for U.S. permanent residency in the past three years are not eligible for this program);

 Is currently living and working in his/her home country (Individuals participating in academic, training or research programs in the United States at the time of application and individuals residing or working outside their home countries at the time of application are not eligible for this program);

 Is currently working on a community project or initiative in his/her home country; and, has at least two years of community development experience at the time of application;

 Is able to begin the program in the United States in 2013, and is committed to returning to his/her home country for a period of two years after completion of the program;

 Is able to receive a U.S. J-1 visa (Individuals who have participated in an exchange visitor program sponsored or funded by the U.S. Government who have not fulfilled their two-year home residency requirement by the time of application are not eligible for this program); and,

 Is proficient in spoken and written English at the time of application.

